title: College roundup: 10-man UVM ties Stony Brook
text:
College roundup: 10-man UVM ties Stony Brook Free Press Sports Staff 10:47 p.m. EDT October 18, 2015 UMBC's Cormac Noael (32) battles for the ball with Vermont's Shane Haley (20) during the men's soccer game between the UMBC Retrievers and the Vermont Catamounts at Virtue Field on Wednesday afternoon. (Photo: BRIAN JENKINS/For the FREE PRESS) CONNECT 1 TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
STONY BROOK, N.Y. - Playing a man down for more than 90 minutes, the University of Vermont men’s soccer team scratched out a 1-1 draw with Stony Brook in America East conference play on Sunday. 
After a red card for defender Jack Shea in the 15th minute, UVM (7-5-2 overall, 2-1-1 league) took the lead on a Seawolves’ own goal in the 42nd minute. Catamounts Greg Walton finished with five saves in the tie. 
Serge Gamwanya equalized for Stony Brook (4-6-3, 1-2-1) on a free kick in the 67th minute and Jason Orban made one save. 
COLLEGE WOMEN’S SOCCER 
• Albany 2, Vermont 0: Kelly Kempf and Mariah Williams each scored in the second half to lift visiting Albany to a shutout win over Vermont in America East play at Virtue Field. 
Ally Ramos made eight saves for the Catamounts (6-7-2, 3-3-1). 
Kiana Rugar set up both goals and Alana Olivieri worked a two-save shutout for the Great Danes (7-8-1, 2-3-1). 
COLLEGE FIELD HOCKEY 
• St. Michael’s 8, St. Thomas Aquinas 0: Breaking out for its biggest offensive outing in eight years, visiting St. Michael’s routed host St. Thomas Aquinas (1-12). 
Abby Dusha led the way with two goals and two assists in the first 14 minutes of the game. Mackenzie Hudson, Carolyn Avery and Jackie Matthews each had a goal and an assist for the Purple Knights (6-8). Morgan Mazanec, Tess Klappe and Katie Leonard added single tallies. 
• Albany 6, Vermont 0: Two-goal days from Anna Bottino and Rachael Billig propelled 10th-ranked Albany to a 6-1 win over host Vermont in America East action at Moulton Winder Field. 
Lena Benwood made three saves for the Catamounts (3-12, 1-4) while Maxi Primus made no saves in the Great Danes (12-2, 4-1) shutout. Read or Share this story: http://bfpne.ws/1RQM7ho TOP VIDEOS
